SIMPLE: rump
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rump
<hw>Rump</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>rumpe</ets>;
akin to D. <ets>romp</ets> trunk, body, LG. <ets>rump</ets>, G.
<ets>rumpf</ets>, Dan. <ets>rumpe</ets> rump, Icel. <ets>rumpr</ets>,
Sw. <ets>rumpa</ets> rump, tail.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The end of the
backbone of an animal, with the parts adjacent; the buttock or
buttocks.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Among butchers, the piece of beef between the
sirloin and the aitchbone piece. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Beef</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <mark>Fig.:</mark> <def>The hind or tail end; a fag-end;
a remnant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><mcol><col><b>Rump Parliament</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>The
Rump</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Eng. Hist.)</fld>, <cd>the remnant of the
Long Parliament after the expulsion by <persfn>Cromwell</persfn> in 1648
of those who opposed his purposes. It was dissolved by
<persfn>Cromwell</persfn> in 1653, but twice revived for brief sessions,
ending finally in 1659.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>Rump</qex> abolished the <org>House of Lords</org>, the
army abolished the <qex>Rump</qex>, and by this army of saints
<persfn>Cromwell</persfn> governed.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>Rump steak</b></col>, <cd>a beefsteak from the rump.</cd>
<au>Goldsmith.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Rumper</ent>⟦br⟧
